Sounds like someone is a little sore that their OS just can't seem to
reach a final shipping date.

> >Angry that after all the gloat about how lean and mean linux is, NT's
> >kernel is less one fifth that size? Tough!

True ( I guess ) - but what does the kernel do, sits there and waits for
you to give it all of NT's subsystems, which ain't that small.  Plus, we
can make whatever changes we want to our kernel to customize it, fix it
or whatever - as for NT, well, we'll wait for the next release and pray
it actually comes.

> >Or that your file system
> >falters more often than it works? (how many times a day does the extfs
> >get corrupted?)
> Okay, let's see a show of hands.  How many people using extfs?  How many
> using ext2fs?  How many using xiafs?  How many using minixfs?  How many
> using minixfs with 32 character filenames?

Hmm...I have use all but xiafs.  I use ext2fs, and before that extfs.  How
many errors have I had? How many corruptions?  When I add them all together
I come up with 0!!!  I can use the above mentioned filesystems, msdos, and
I think I can even read OS/2 (and maybe even HPFS)

> >For crying out loud, you even have to recompile the
> >whole os in order to add the littlest of drivers!

When was the last time I recompiled the whole kernel?  I dunno.  I just
added a sound patch yesterday to play digitized sound via the PC speaker
(can NT do that?) and I recomiled 4 files and relinked, and it worked
perfect (quietly, but perfect.)  Hey, at least I can compile my kernel :)

> >You know what your problem is? You stare at your os too much! I mean,
> >let's face it, you have *NO* applcations,
> Emacs.  Tex.  Ghostscript.  X.  Any application running under X for which
> source is available.  Any Unix utility for which source is available.

You're right, we have no applications - in a shrink-wrapped overpriced box.
(Actually, there are about 3 companies that now sell Linux apps.)
But we do have the whole internet to pick our software from.  If I have
no applications, I wonder what the hell is taking up 73% of my 110 meg
partition.  Only 6 megs of it is guitar tab.

> To my knowledge, there's one, and only one, application that doesn't exist
> for Linux directly, and that's a word processor.  Everything else is there.

There is always doc.    It wasn't written just for Linux, but it works

> And oh, by the way, just about any language you want is available just for
> the asking.  FOR FREE.  That means: basic, fortran, C, C++, lisp, prolog,
> smalltalk, Ada, etc.

And they are all pretty much intercompatiable.  IE, I can easily link my
fortran and c code, something that is a pain under MS's world.

> >and as such all you can do
> >is gaze at your os, and hence slowly you acquire an unpalatable taste
> >for it! They have drag and drop they say! Well, name *one* application
> >where you can actually drag something and drop into another app. You
> >don't even have a file manager for pete's sake!

Lets see, there is Xdm, which does okay, or  - wait - I run xmfm, the
Motif File Manager.  As for drag and drop.  olwm supports it, Motif
supports it.  Hell, I can even drag and drop between text applications
on different virtual consoles.  Can you do that?  Not without the windows
scratchpad thing.

> I think you'll find, like I have, that there are certain cases where it's
> real useful to have a file manager around and there are others where the
> command line is a lot faster.  Just depends.  But a file manager isn't
> the be all and end all that you seem to think.
> I agree that X could use a good one, though.

I'll agree on that, but why move my mouse to a file, click, click on
delete, when I can just do rm -fR /user/brilear and kill a file, directory
or whatever.

> >We don't mind the os as much as long as it get the job done. And we
> >have the tools for that, none of which you have, or ever will. Do you
> >have Winword? Word perfect?

Wait...to be a good os, you have to have Weird Defect, er Word Perfect.
Give me a break.  What are your other qualifications - Wordstar?
Visicalc?  Like I said above, we have all the tools on the internet.
You have ftp.cica.indiana.edu.

> >Lotus 123? *Any* spreadsheet?
> Yup.  Oleo, from the FSF.  Or SC.
Hmm..didn't know about that... Have to FTP and simply recompile it and
I'll have it.

> >Procomm?
> You're joking, right?  There are a number of communication programs floating
> around for Linux, some of which do more than Procomm.  But the big killer
> that Linux has is:
>     UUCP.

Bingo...gee, my e-mail get's delivered right to my house. If it wasn't for
my sister using the phone, I could set it up to be automatic.  Gee, I can
log into another computer via Kermit or Seyon (a telecom app developed on
Linux).  Or I can connect my computer directly to the internet via slip
and get more use out of my phone line/modem, than dialing into a bbs
and downloading GIF's.

> >Go figure. And on top of that we now have the superior os!

Since when does higher price = superiority.

> >It wasn't even posted
> >to your group for crying out loud! Whay are so offended? so bitter? so
> >vulgar? Go play elsewhere with your toy os! Don't bother us in our
> >group.

Right, you'll have enuff problems as is with NT alone.  Don't wanna make
any more traffic than the bug reports.  Bitter, nah.  Vulgar, rarely,
offended, yes.  Do I care - no.  I'm just killing time before Lunch.
I think it's a pity that you are blinded by Microsoft and their ways
and can't make a valid judgement on Linux (as you've been corrected)

