From: iiitac@swan.pyr (Alan Cox)
Subject: Re: A question about the SLS sysinstall script's copyright
Date: Fri, 20 Aug 1993 15:04:45 GMT

In article <1993Aug20.062002.21169@cc.gatech.edu> byron@cc.gatech.edu (Byron A Jeff) writes:
>In article <1993Aug19.070534.6725@jonh.wimsey.bc.ca>,
>John Henders <jhenders@jonh.wimsey.bc.ca> wrote:
>>
>
>2) The copyright notice on doinstall clearly states 
>
>   # copyright Softlanding Software 92,93.  Distribute freely, don't restrict
>
>   Patrick did that. So can a copyright on a distributed
>   work be later modified especially when the distribution copyright plainly
>   states that is can be distributed freely?
No you cannot revoke any permissions granted, unless you included the right
to revoke them in the intial granting (roughly speaking - its not actually
exactly that simple).
>
>3) Then there's the matter of the GPL. See my other post. From my reading of
>   it Peter's scripts have to GPL'ed or he can't distribute it. By putting
>   a non redistribute copyright on the scripts he's violating the GPL.
>   Patrick followed the GPL almost to the letter (he didn't put in the scripts
>   that he had modified them and the date modified - an oversight I'm sure). 
Nothing says the scripts are GPL'd. Nor does he have to make them GPL 
material. Search the GPL for 'mere aggregation'. There are Peters scripts
unless he states otherwise which he doesn't. He just says distribute freely
and then contradicts his statement elsewhere.
>
>4) Lastly I think Peter oversteps his copyright (old and new) by saying that
>   any distribution that includes his code must be called SLS. As long as
Indeed I can find no such condition in the older material I checked. Maybe
we should start releasing useful tools that you cannot put in a distribution 
called SLS. Had he always said so I'd have no argument about the technicality
of SLS being SLS only. Morally its a different story.
>   there is a copyright attribution and a Banner attribution on execution
>   for the SLS code, the claim of "taking the credit for the work of others"
>   is negated. Patrick does both in Slackware. In fact in the ANNOUNCE file
>   is the following statement:
>
>"This release is based largely on the SLS system, but has been enhanced and
>modified substantially."
>  
The only person who could be held to be taking credit for thr work of others
is Peter. A lot of people put all the Linux stuff together, helped debug SLS
and support it on the net. Now he has competition he immediately goes off
and starts causing hassle. Linux is meant to be shared. The whole GPL is
meant to be about not rewriting and reinventing, yet the man shipping tons
of GPL stuff is saying rewrite or else.
I've never been impressed with the lack of source code supplied with SLS,
maybe it is about time someone in the FSF sat on SLS.

Alan
iiitac@pyr.swan.ac.uk

